\begin{prop}
Let us denote the density of states measures of $\hat{H}^{e}, \hat{H}^{o}$ and $\hat{H}$ by  
$\hat{\nu}^{e}, \hat{\nu}^{o}$ and $\hat{\nu}$, respectively.
Then, $\hat{\nu}^{e}, \hat{\nu}^{o}$ and $\hat{\nu}$ define the same measure. In particular,  
the spectra of $\hat{H}^{e}, \hat{H}^{o}$ and $\hat{H}$ all coincide.
\end{prop} 

\begin{proof}
By Lemma \ref{twin}, $A^{e}$ and $A^{o}$ are linearly repetitive. 
Therefore, by Theorem 6.1 of \cite{LP} and Theorem 3 of \cite{LS2} and 
Lemma \ref{twin}, we have $\hat{\nu}^{e} = \hat{\nu}^{o}$. Since $\hat{H} = \hat{H}^{e} \oplus \hat{H}^{o}$, 
we get $\hat{\nu}^{e} = \hat{\nu}^{o} = \hat{\nu}$. 
\end{proof} 

By this proposition, we will restrict our attention to $\hat{H}$ below. 

